      "markdown": "# Cable Types\n\n## What\n\nCable types are the physical connectors and leads used to move data, video, and power.\n\nFor this project, the learner is mainly learning to tell common shapes apart: RJ45, USB-A, USB-C, HDMI, and Thunderbolt over USB-C.\n\n## Why\n\nCable recognition is one of the fastest wins in A+ study.\n\nIf the learner can identify the connector shape quickly, the rest of the troubleshooting flow becomes easier.\n\n## How\n\n- Learn the shape first.\n- Learn the purpose second.\n- Match the cable to the port before worrying about speed tiers or marketing labels.\n\nNotes:\n\n- USB Type-C is the connector shape, not the same thing as every protocol that can use it.\n- Thunderbolt uses the USB-C shape on many devices, but not every USB-C port is Thunderbolt.\n- HDMI is the standard display connector in this set.\n\nSources:\n\n- USB-IF Type-C guidelines on reversible plug orientation and cable direction: [USB Type-C cable and connector guidelines](https://www.usb.org/sites/default/files/usb_type-c_language_product_and_packaging_guidelines_20230320.pdf)\n- Intel overview of Thunderbolt over USB-C: [Thunderbolt Technology](https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/architecture-and-technology/thunderbolt/overview.html)\n- HDMI overview and cable resources: [HDMI Specifications and Programs](https://www.hdmi.org/spec/index)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Create the cable-types page shell.\n- [ ] Add a visual shape comparison.\n- [ ] Add a short learner example.\n- [x] Link the cable matching lab.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Start Connector Match](../../app/index.html#module=drag)\n"
