      "content_status": "source-backed draft",
      "source_status": "source links added",
      "markdown": "# Motherboards\n\n## What\n\nA motherboard is the main circuit board in a PC or laptop.\n\nIt is the place where the processor, memory, storage connectors, power delivery, firmware, and expansion paths meet.\n\n## Why\n\nMotherboards matter because many A+ questions are really about finding where a part connects or what role a slot plays.\n\nOnce the learner can read the board, they can reason about upgrades and common faults more confidently.\n\n## How\n\n- Start with board layout.\n- Find the CPU socket or soldered CPU area.\n- Find the memory slots.\n- Find storage connectors, power connectors, and front-panel or port headers.\n\nSources:\n\n- CompTIA A+ Core 1 public overview: [CompTIA A+ Core 1 (V15)](https://www.comptia.org/en/certifications/a/core-1-and-2-v15/)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Create the motherboards page shell.\n- [ ] Add a board-layout visual.\n- [ ] Add common slot and header labels.\n- [x] Link the hardware drill.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Start Connector Match](../../app/index.html#module=drag)\n"
