      "content_status": "source-backed draft",
      "source_status": "source links added",
      "markdown": "# BIOS/UEFI\n\n## What\n\nBIOS and UEFI are firmware layers that help start the computer before the operating system loads.\n\nUEFI is the modern replacement for legacy BIOS on most current devices.\n\n## Why\n\nThis topic helps the learner understand startup, boot mode, secure boot, and why newer systems usually behave differently from older ones.\n\n## How\n\n- Learn that firmware starts the machine before the OS.\n- Learn that UEFI is the current standard on modern systems.\n- Learn that some devices can still emulate BIOS behavior for compatibility.\n- Connect the boot mode to partition style and security behavior.\n\nSources:\n\n- Microsoft overview of UEFI as the successor to BIOS: [Windows deployment scenarios and tools](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-deployment-scenarios-and-tools)\n- Microsoft boot-mode guidance: [Boot to UEFI Mode or legacy BIOS mode](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/boot-to-uefi-mode-or-legacy-bios-mode?view=windows-11)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Create the BIOS-UEFI page shell.\n- [ ] Add a simple boot-flow diagram.\n- [ ] Add a BIOS versus UEFI comparison card.\n- [x] Link the startup practice activity.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Start Connector Match](../../app/index.html#module=drag)\n"
