      "content_status": "source-backed draft",
      "source_status": "source links added",
      "markdown": "# Cloud Computing\n\n## What\n\nCloud computing is the delivery of computing services over the internet.\n\nThose services can include servers, storage, networking, software, and other managed resources.\n\n## Why\n\nLearners need a simple cloud model because A+ questions often compare cloud services with local hardware and ask what the cloud is good for.\n\nIt also helps explain why a company might rent services instead of buying and maintaining everything itself.\n\n## How\n\n- Think of the cloud as rented computing power and storage.\n- The provider owns and manages the remote infrastructure.\n- The customer uses only the services it needs.\n- Common service models are IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS.\n- Common deployment models are public cloud, private cloud, and hybrid cloud.\n\nExamples:\n\n- IaaS gives you more control over servers, storage, and networking.\n- PaaS gives you a managed platform for building and deploying apps.\n- SaaS gives you a finished application delivered as a service.\n\nSources:\n\n- Microsoft Azure cloud computing definition: [What Is Cloud Computing?](https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/cloud-computing-dictionary/what-is-cloud-computing/)\n- Google Cloud cloud computing definition and service models: [What is Cloud Computing?](https://cloud.google.com/learn/what-is-cloud-computing)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Write the first original cloud-computing page.\n- [x] Define cloud, service models, and deployment models in plain language.\n- [x] Add authoritative source links.\n- [ ] Add a cloud-service comparison card.\n- [x] Link the cloud flash-card lab.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Review Visual Cards](../../app/index.html#module=flash)\n"
