      "content_status": "source-backed draft",
      "source_status": "source links added",
      "markdown": "# Networking Basics\n\n## What\n\nNetworking basics is the set of ideas that explain how devices talk to each other and to the internet.\n\nAt this level, the learner should know the roles of switches, routers, access points, and DNS.\n\n## Why\n\nThis is the foundation for the networking part of A+.\n\nIf the learner understands the role of each device, later troubleshooting steps stop feeling random.\n\n## How\n\n- A switch connects devices inside the local network.\n- A router connects networks and usually links the local network to the internet.\n- An access point gives wireless devices a way onto the network.\n- DNS turns human-friendly names into addresses computers can use.\n\nUseful framing:\n\n- Switch = local device traffic.\n- Router = between networks.\n- Access point = wireless entry.\n- DNS = name lookup.\n\nSources:\n\n- Cisco overview of switches, routers, and access points: [Networking basics](https://www.cisco.com/site/us/en/learn/topics/small-business/networking-basics.html)\n- Cisco explanation of DNS in network communications: [Understand DNS](https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/umbrella/225283-understand-dns.html)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Write the first original networking page.\n- [x] Define switch, router, access point, and DNS in plain language.\n- [x] Add authoritative source links.\n- [ ] Add a network-role visual.\n- [x] Link the network path activity.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Trace Network Path](../../app/index.html#module=topology)\n"
