      "content_status": "source-backed draft",
      "source_status": "source links added",
      "markdown": "# Wireless Networks\n\n## What\n\nWireless networks let devices connect without a cable.\n\nIn practice, most learners meet this as Wi-Fi on a home, school, or office network.\n\n## Why\n\nWireless is everywhere, so A+ learners need to understand both the convenience and the extra risk it brings.\n\nThat makes wireless one of the most practical networking topics to learn early.\n\n## How\n\n- A wireless access point or wireless router provides radio coverage.\n- A Wi-Fi client connects from within range.\n- Strong passwords and encryption matter because the signal travels through the air.\n- Wireless is convenient, but the device still depends on the same network ideas as wired networking.\n\nUseful framing:\n\n- Wired and wireless are both network access.\n- Wi-Fi is the common WLAN technology.\n- Good security settings matter more because nearby devices can attempt to join.\n\nSources:\n\n- Cisco explanation of Wi-Fi networks: [What is a Wi-Fi network?](https://www.cisco.com/site/us/en/learn/topics/networking/what-is-a-wi-fi-network.html)\n- Cisco Wi-Fi security overview: [What is Wi-Fi Security?](https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/wireless/what-is-wi-fi-security.html)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Write the first original wireless page.\n- [x] Define Wi-Fi and wireless access in plain language.\n- [x] Add authoritative source links.\n- [ ] Add a wireless-versus-wired visual.\n- [x] Link the wireless practice activity.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Trace Network Path](../../app/index.html#module=topology)\n"
