      "markdown": "# Troubleshooting Networks\n\nWhat\n\nNetwork troubleshooting means finding out why a device cannot connect, cannot reach the internet, or cannot reach a specific service. The problem might be Wi-Fi, Ethernet, DNS, IP addressing, a router, a firewall, or a service outage.\n\nWhy\n\nThis topic matters because many \"network\" failures are really connection, address, or name-resolution problems. A learner who can sort those layers quickly can avoid chasing the wrong fix.\n\nHow\n\nStart with the visible checks:\n\n- Confirm the device is connected to the right network.\n- Check Wi-Fi, cable, port, and airplane mode or adapter state.\n- Test another site, then another device.\n- Check IP address, gateway, and DNS.\n- Reset the adapter or network stack if needed.\n- Restart the router or access point if the issue is local.\n\nTypical signs:\n\n- Connected but no internet.\n- No network icon or limited connectivity.\n- Slow page loads or only some sites failing.\n- DNS errors.\n- Printer, file share, or app access failing even though Wi-Fi looks fine.\n\nSources\n\n- [Microsoft Support: Fix Wi-Fi connection issues in Windows](https://support.microsoft.com/en-US/windows/fix-network-connection-issues-in-windows-10-166a28c4-14c1-bdb1-473c-09c1571455d8)\n- [Microsoft Support: Essential Network Settings and Tasks in Windows](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/check-your-network-connection-status-efb4fb41-f751-567a-f60f-aac9114659a5)\n- [Microsoft Support: Windows troubleshooters](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/use-a-troubleshooter-with-windows-10-cc3cb85b-91d7-7e56-8ce1-db50b4d18d0b)\n\nChecklist:\n\n- [x] Check the active connection first.\n- [x] Separate local network from internet issues.\n- [x] Test IP, DNS, and reachability.\n- [x] Reset or restart only after the basics.\n\nPractice\n\n- [Open Ticket Board](../../app/index.html#module=tickets)\n"
